-1. Grab a pair of cheap bluetooth headphones.  Will be used for audio prompts, etc.
0. install minimal raspberry pi os configuration.  
1. enable camera via raspi-config.
1a. connect to your local network via raspi-config
1b. enable i2c communication
1c. if applicable, change country code for keyboard.
1d. if applicable, enable sshd.
1e. reboot
2. apt-get update ; apt-get upgrade -y; apt-get dist-upgrade -y
2a. reboot
3. sudo apt-get install sense-hat build-essential git
4. sudo apt-get install python3-picamera -y 
5. sudo apt-get install bluealsa -y
5a. sudo service bluealsa start
5b. sudo apt-get install libttspico-utils
5c. pico2wave --wave=out.wav "Your headphones work, yay!"
5d. sudo bluetoothctl 
5e. scan on
5f. Turn on headphones, and note the newly added device. (may need to be in paring mode).
5fa. Note that for the following lines, the address C4:45:67:23:29:F4 is used for a pair of headphones.  Use your values instead.
5g. pair C4:45:67:23:29:F4 #### Note this address, we will configure your device in a second...
5h. trust C4:45:67:23:29:F4
5i. connect C4:45:67:23:29:F4 (should hear a beep on your audio device).
5j. quit
5k. aplay -D bluealsa:HCI=hci0,DEV=C4:45:67:23:29:F4,PROFILE=a2dp ./out.wav # You should get a congratulations message on your headphones.
6. wget https://bootstrap.pypa.io/get-pip.py
9. git clone https://github.com/japharl/kapcode.git
10. sudo chmod -R 777 /home/pi/kapcode/*
11. sudo chown -R pi:pi /home/pi/kapcode/*
12. sudo chmod 777 /etc/rc.local
12aa. mv out.wav ./kapcode/
12a. cd /home/pi/kapcode/
12b. sudo perl bluetooth.pl # follow prompts
12c. aplay -D bluealsa out.wav # should hear audio prompt.
13. sudo apt-get install cpanminus
15. sudo cpanm Proc::Background File::Path File::Slurper
16. sudo vi /etc/rc.local
# Add line:
nohup bash -x /home/pi/kapcode/init.sh &


Partially built upon instructions here: https://robotzero.one/pi-zero-w-bluetooth-voice/ 
